	abstract = {We include a fully coupled treatment of metal and dust enrichment into the {DELPHI} semi-analytic model of galaxy formation to explain the dust content of 13 Lyman break galaxies ({LBGs}) detected by the Atacama Large millimetre Array ({ALMA}) {REBELS} Large Program at z  7. We find that the galaxy dust mass, Md, is regulated by the combination of Type {II} supernova dust production, astration, shock destruction, and ejection in outflows; grain growth (with a standard time-scale 0 = 30 Myr) plays a negligible role. The model predicts a dust-to-stellar mass ratio of \${\textbackslash}sim 0.07{\textbackslash}!-{\textbackslash}!0.1\{\{{\textbackslash} {\textbackslash}rm per{\textbackslash} cent\}\}\$ and a {UV}-to-total star formation rate relation such that log({UV}) = -0.05 [log()]2 + 0.86 log() - 0.05 (implying that 55-80 per cent of the star formation is obscured) for {REBELS} galaxies with stellar mass \$M\_* = 10{\textasciicircum}\{9\}{\textbackslash}!-{\textbackslash}!10{\textasciicircum}\{10\} {\textbackslash}rm M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$. This relation reconciles the intrinsic {UV} luminosity of {LBGs} with their observed luminosity function at z = 7. However, 2 out of the 13 systems show dust-to-stellar mass ratios (\${\textbackslash}sim 0.94{\textbackslash}!-{\textbackslash}!1.1\{\{{\textbackslash} {\textbackslash}rm per{\textbackslash} cent\}\}\$) that are up to 18 times larger than expected from the fiducial relation. Due to the physical coupling between dust and metal enrichment, even decreasing 0 to very low values (0.3 Myr) only increases the dust-to-stellar mass ratio by a factor of {\textasciitilde}2. Given that grain growth is not a viable explanation for such high observed ratios of the dust-to-stellar mass, we propose alternative solutions.},
