	abstract = {We study spatially resolved scaling relations among stars, dust, and gas in ten nearby spiral galaxies. In a preceding paper Abdurro'uf et al. (2022), we have derived spatially resolved properties of the stellar population and dust by panchromatic spectral energy distribution ({SED}) fitting using {piXedfit}. Now, we investigate resolved star formation (\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm {SFR}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{*\}\$) and dust scaling relations. While the relations with all sub-galactic regions of the galaxies are reasonably tight (\${\textbackslash}sigma {\textbackslash}lesssim 0.3\$ dex), we find that most of the scaling relations exhibit galaxy-to-galaxy variations in normalization and shape. Only two relations of \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm dust\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm gas\}\$ and \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm dust\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$ do not show noticeable galaxy-to-galaxy variations among our sample galaxies. We further investigate correlations among the scaling relations. We find significant correlations among the normalization of the \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm {SFR}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{*\}\$ relations, which suggest that galaxies with higher levels of resolved \${\textbackslash}text\{H\}\_\{2\}\$ fraction (\$f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$) tend to have higher levels of resolved star formation efficiency ({SFE}) and specific star formation rate ({sSFR}). We also observe that galaxies with higher levels of resolved dust-to-stellar mass ratios tend to have higher levels of resolved {sSFR}, {SFE}, and \$f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$. Moreover, we find that galaxies with higher global {sSFR} and less compact morphology tend to have higher levels of the resolved {sSFR}, {SFE}, and \$f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$, which can explain the variations in the normalization of the \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_\{2\}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm {SFR}\}\$--\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{*\}\$ relationships. Overall, we observe indications of the contributions of both global and local factors in governing the star formation process in galaxies.},
