	shorttitle = {A {JWST}/{NIRCam} Study of Key Contributors to Reionization},
	abstract = {Spitzer/{IRAC} imaging has revealed that the brightest \$z{\textbackslash}sim7-8\$ galaxies often exhibit young ages and strong nebular line emission, hinting at high ionizing efficiency among early galaxies. However, {IRAC}'s limited sensitivity has long hindered efforts to study the fainter, more numerous population often thought largely responsible for reionization. Here we use {CEERS} {JWST}/{NIRCam} data to characterize 118 {UV}-faint (median M\$\_\{{UV}\}=-19.6\$) \$z{\textbackslash}sim6.5-8\$ galaxies. We find that the {SEDs} are typically dominated by young (\${\textbackslash}sim\$10-50 Myr), low-mass (\$M\_{\textbackslash}ast{\textbackslash}sim10{\textasciicircum}8{\textbackslash} M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$) stellar populations, with no need for extreme masses (\${\textbackslash}sim10{\textasciicircum}\{11\} M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$) among our sample in contrast to recent findings in {CEERS}. Considering previous studies of {UV}-bright (M\$\_\{{UV}\}{\textbackslash}sim-22\$) \$z{\textbackslash}sim7-8\$ galaxies, we find evidence for a strong (5-10\${\textbackslash}times\$) increase in specific star formation rate toward lower luminosities (median {sSFR}=82 Gyr\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$ in {CEERS}). The larger {sSFRs} imply a more dominant contribution from {OB} stars in the relatively numerous {UV}-faint population, perhaps suggesting that these galaxies are very efficient ionizing agents (median \${\textbackslash}xi\_\{ion\}=10{\textasciicircum}\{25.7\}\$ erg\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$ Hz). In spite of their much larger {sSFRs}, we find no significant increase in [{OIII}]\$+\$H\${\textbackslash}beta\$ {EWs} towards fainter M\$\_\{{UV}\}\$ (median \${\textbackslash}approx\$780 \${\textbackslash}mathring\{A\}\$). If confirmed, this may indicate that a substantial fraction of our {CEERS} galaxies possess extremely low metallicities (\${\textbackslash}lesssim\$3\% \$Z\_{\textbackslash}odot\$) where [{OIII}] emission is suppressed. Alternatively, high ionizing photon escape fractions or bursty star formation histories can also weaken the nebular lines in a subset of our {CEERS} galaxies. While the majority of our objects are very blue (median \${\textbackslash}beta=-2.0\$), we identify a significant tail of very dusty galaxies (\${\textbackslash}beta{\textbackslash}sim-1\$) at \${\textbackslash}approx\$0.5\$L\_\{{UV}\}{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}ast\$ which may contribute significantly to the \$z{\textbackslash}sim7-8\$ star formation rate density.},
	number = {{arXiv}:2208.14999},
