	shorttitle = {The {SAMI} Galaxy Survey},
	abstract = {We study environmental quenching using the spatial distribution of current star-formation and stellar population ages with the full {SAMI} Galaxy Survey. By using a star-formation concentration index [C-index, defined as log10(r\_\{50,Halpha\}/r\_\{50,cont\})], we separate our sample into regular galaxies (C-index{\textgreater}-0.2) and galaxies with centrally concentrated star-formation ({SF}-concentrated; C-index{\textless}-0.2). Concentrated star-formation is a potential indicator of galaxies currently undergoing `outside-in' quenching. Our environments cover ungrouped galaxies, low-mass groups (M\_200{\textless}10{\textasciicircum}12.5 M\_sun), high-mass groups (M\_200 in the range 10{\textasciicircum}\{12.5-14\} M\_sun) and clusters (M\_200{\textgreater}10{\textasciicircum}14 M\_sun). We find the fraction of {SF}-concentrated galaxies increases as halo mass increases with 9{\textbackslash}pm2 per cent, 8{\textbackslash}pm3 per cent, 19{\textbackslash}pm4 per cent and 29{\textbackslash}pm4 per cent for ungrouped galaxies, low-mass groups, high-mass groups and clusters, respectively. We interpret these results as evidence for `outside-in' quenching in groups and clusters. To investigate the quenching time-scale in {SF}-concentrated galaxies, we calculate light-weighted age (Age\_L) and mass-weighted age (Age\_M) using full spectral fitting, as well as the Dn4000 and Hdelta\_A indices. We assume that the average galaxy age radial profile before entering a group or cluster is similar to ungrouped regular galaxies. At large radius (1-2 R\_e), {SF}-concentrated galaxies in high-mass groups have older ages than ungrouped regular galaxies with an age difference of 1.83{\textbackslash}pm0.38 Gyr for Age\_L and 1.34{\textbackslash}pm0.56 Gyr for Age\_M. This suggests that while `outside-in' quenching can be effective in groups, the process will not quickly quench the entire galaxy. In contrast, the ages at 1-2 R\_e of cluster {SF}-concentrated galaxies and ungrouped regular galaxies are consistent (0.19{\textbackslash}pm0.21 Gyr for Age\_L, 0.40{\textbackslash}pm0.61 Gyr for Age\_M), suggesting the quenching process must be rapid.},
