	shorttitle = {A Long Time Ago in a Galaxy Far, Far Away},
	abstract = {We report the discovery of a candidate galaxy with a photo-z of z {\textasciitilde} 12 in the first epoch of the James Webb Space Telescope ({JWST}) Cosmic Evolution Early Release Science Survey. Following conservative selection criteria, we identify a source with a robust z phot = \$\{11.8\}\_\{-0.2\}{\textasciicircum}\{+0.3\}\$ (1 uncertainty) with m F200W = 27.3 and 7 detections in five filters. The source is not detected at  {\textless} 1.4 m in deep imaging from both Hubble Space Telescope ({HST}) and {JWST} and has faint {\textasciitilde}3 detections in {JWST} F150W and {HST} F160W, which signal a Ly break near the red edge of both filters, implying z {\textasciitilde} 12. This object (Maisie's Galaxy) exhibits F115W - F200W {\textgreater} 1.9 mag (2 lower limit) with a blue continuum slope, resulting in 99.6\% of the photo-z probability distribution function favoring z {\textgreater} 11. All data-quality images show no artifacts at the candidate's position, and independent analyses consistently find a strong preference for z {\textgreater} 11. Its colors are inconsistent with Galactic stars, and it is resolved (r h = 340  14 pc). Maisie's Galaxy has log M */M  {\textasciitilde} 8.5 and is highly star-forming (log {sSFR} {\textasciitilde} -8.2 yr-1), with a blue rest-{UV} color ( {\textasciitilde} -2.5) indicating little dust, though not extremely low metallicity. While the presence of this source is in tension with most predictions, it agrees with empirical extrapolations assuming {UV} luminosity functions that smoothly decline with increasing redshift. Should follow-up spectroscopy validate this redshift, our universe was already aglow with galaxies less than 400 Myr after the Big Bang.},
